<h3 id="overview">Overview</h3>
<p>
    <code>CustomSanitizer</code> is the single contract every sanitizer provider implements:
    <code>sanitize(html, config)</code> &rarr; safe-html, narrowing untrusted markup to an allowed element/attribute
    schema. The native <code>Element.setHTML()</code> default and the DOMPurify production-floor adapter satisfy this
    same interface, which is what lets <a href="/plugs/customsanitizerregistry/">the registry</a> treat them
    interchangeably.
</p>

<h3 id="standards">Web Standards Alignment</h3>
<we-data-table><table>
    <tr><th>Standard</th><th>Status</th><th>How We Adopt It</th></tr>
    <tr>
        <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Sanitizer">Sanitizer API</a></td>
        <td>Progressive</td>
        <td>The default provider wraps the native sanitizer's allow-list configuration.</td>
    </tr>
</table></we-data-table>

<h3 id="interface">Interface</h3>
{% highlight "typescript" %}
interface CustomSanitizer {
    /** Narrow untrusted markup to an allowed element/attribute schema. */
    sanitize(html: string, config?: SanitizerConfig): string;
}
{% endhighlight %}

<p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mt-4">
    Satisfied alike by the native <code>Element.setHTML()</code> default and the DOMPurify adapter registered through
    the <a href="/plugs/customsanitizerregistry/"><code>CustomSanitizerRegistry</code></a>.
    See <a href="/projects/webvalidation/">Web Validation</a>.
</p>
